    t2_title: 'Round to a friendly number, then adjust',
    t2_body: 'Instead of working with awkward numbers, <strong>round one number to the nearest 10 or 100, operate, then subtract the difference</strong>. Dramatically reduces cognitive load.',
    t2_ex1_label: 'Addition — 68 + 47', t2_ex1_step1: 'Round 68 → 70 (+2)',
    t2_ex2_label: 'Subtraction — 293 − 148', t2_ex2_step1: 'Round 293 → 300 (+7)',
    t3_title: 'Spot compatible pairs first',
    t3_body: 'When adding a list of numbers, <strong>scan for pairs that sum to 10 or 100 first</strong>. Add those together, then handle the rest. Turns hard addition into easy addition.',
    t3_ex_label: 'Example — 37 + 53 + 24 + 16 + 45', t3_ex_step1: 'Spot: 37 + 53 = 90 · 24 + 16 = 40', t3_ex_comment: '// Two hard additions become one easy one',
    t4_title: 'Count up instead of subtracting',
    t4_body: 'For subtraction, ask: <em>"what do I add to reach the target?"</em> <strong>Count up from the smaller number in convenient steps</strong> — eliminates borrowing entirely.',
    t4_ex_label: 'Example — 1000 − 437',
    t4_body2: "This is how shopkeepers made change before electronic tills. For large gaps it's significantly faster than direct subtraction.",
    mult_h2: 'Multiplication', mult_intro: "Four shortcuts that cover 80% of multiplication you'll encounter outside a textbook.",
    t5_title: 'Use the distributive property',
    t5_body: '<strong>Split one number into easy parts, multiply each, then add the results.</strong> The most general multiplication technique — works for any number, any size.',
    t5_ex1_label: 'Example — 47 × 8', t5_ex2_label: 'Example — 23 × 14',
    t6_title: 'Multiply by 5: halve, then ×10',
    t6_body: '5 = 10 ÷ 2. So <strong>any ×5 becomes: halve the number, then shift the decimal.</strong> Always faster than multiplying by 5 directly.',
    t7_title: 'Multiply by 9: ×10 then subtract the original',
    t7_body: '9 = 10 − 1, so <strong>n × 9 = (n × 10) − n</strong>. Same logic applies to ×11 (add n), ×19, ×99 — anything near a round number.',
    t7_ex_label: 'Example — 67 × 9',
    t8_title: 'Multiply by 11: add the neighbours',
    t8_body: 'For any two-digit number × 11: <strong>write the first digit, add the two digits together for the middle, write the last digit.</strong> If the middle sum exceeds 9, carry 1 to the left.',
    t8_ex1_label: 'Example — 43 × 11', t8_ex1_step: '4 _ 3 → middle: 4 + 3 = 7',
    t8_ex2_label: 'Example — 78 × 11', t8_ex2_step: '7 _ 8 → middle: 7 + 8 = 15, carry 1',
    pct_h2: 'Percentages', pct_intro: 'The most practically useful mental math skill for everyday life: tips, discounts, tax, interest. All comes down to these four strategies.',
    t9_title: 'Find 1%, then scale up',
    t9_body: '1% of any number = move the decimal two places left. <strong>Once you have 1%, build any percentage by scaling.</strong>',
    t9_ex_label: 'Example — 13% of 400',
    t10_title: 'Flip the percentage (x% of y = y% of x)',
    t10_body: 'Percentage is commutative. <strong>If one direction looks hard, flip it.</strong> 4% of 75 is identical to 75% of 4 — but one is trivial.',
